Goal of the simulator:
The goal of the simulation is to predict the layout of particles in a medium after a certain time given the mass flow rate, the medium, and the particles properties like tis radius, density and more.
It was specifically designed to predict the coating layout of TiO2 particles. A good explanation can be found in project 3A on teams.

What was here before?
When first starting this project, students had worked on a simulation with agglomerating particles. Those files can be found under CODE SOURCE. They had a brownian motion simulator that would simulate agglomeration or collision depending on a coefficient. It is well commented, and inspired me for the code, even though 95% of the algorithms had to be rethought for efficiency and reliability: tunneling was happening, particles were skipping each other… However, It was a great start.

Thought Process:
This next section will explain step by step the coding process. Highlighting the different parts of the code.

The main concern was run time and accuracy. Being able to simulate millions of particles on a single machine with reliability and following physics law to ensure applicability to the real world.

To do so, the concept of message per interface also known as mpi was introduced to the project. MPI (links below)

is a downloadable library that allows you to separate the different cores of processors in your machine. It is usable in a super calculator. It allows you to treat cores as a computers and manage the communications between them.

In this numerical simulation, mpi is used to separate the domain like a cube in a rubik’s cube. Once particles leave the cube, they will be sent to the according neighboring processor.

Step 1: Transporting a single particle across different processors in 2D.
The most part of the script code is moving particles across different processors. To ensure no particles would be lost, ghost zones were create (image here)The color of the line represent the ownership of the line to a certain zone - numbered 0-8. Depending on the ownership the inequality signs will have an equal sign or not of the condition loops to ensure a particle can only be in one zone at one time for a designated processor. A particle can only be in one “local zone” at once but can be in ghost zones of the neighboring zones.

Step 2: Introduce collisions (links below)
After studying particles dynamics, collision functions were created as can be seen in particle_interactions.py . In the for loop, the first thing that is done is updating the velocities. Collision coding happens in 3 steps: Broad_detect which returns the particles within a certain distance d, narrow_detect which predicts if the particles will hit each other during the delta t and returns the time of collision and first collision. And update_particles_collision which returns the updates Attributes values after collision. 

Step 3: Add Brownian motion (links below)
Brownian motion is approximating the effect of smaller particles (median like air or water) around the studied particles (here TiO2). In this simulation we are using Ornstein Uhlenbeck’s equation.   Step 4: Agglomeration
Particles can also be agglomerating, if their velocity isn’t great enough to bounce back (see Lennard Jones). Hence, another function with the same return than collision, called update_particles_agglomeration can be found in particle_interactions.py

Step 5: Spin
Starts with the center of gravity, stopped here for now


Step 6: User Interface
To make the simulator accessible, a user interface where the user gets to choose clearly their set up and see the progress as the code is running was required. The code for those can be found in :
Gui.py for the user interface and Progress_gui.py for the progress bars.

Errors codes and meaning:

Example: 
The position  [66.68250616 99.99      ]  for particule  145  in proc:  4  is different than in the master at t =  762 
  which is :  [ 0.   99.99] => This error is due to a mismatch between one processor already merged with the master and the new processor being added. Happens 1/30 000 particles or so. I believe it is due to the particle accelerating, and hence not having time in the buffer to be updated in and hence transferred to the next processor, the particle was retrieved explaining the right position in the master.  I wonder why the error is still showing…

Missing indices: []  ... total: 0
Example values: []
=> If the number is anything but 0 it means the spawning zone was too small for the number of particles that needed to be generated. As 2 particles cannot be on top of one another.   Try reducing the number of particles of increasing the domain.

